Nov 12 2009 	We were very happy with our hotel choice.	We just returned from 4 days (3 nights) at the Monte Carlo in Las Vegas, and we are very happy with our choice of hotel. We had read some rather negative reviews here, after having made our reservations, and were a little concerned that we might end up disappointed. Wrong.Check in, at 11am, was smooth and quick. As was stated here before, there were several lines along the registration desk, and it was luck of the draw as far as choosing the best line went. But there was a manager guiding people to shorter lines, and he quickly opened up two more stations. We had booked three separate rooms and had expected to only be able to check in, leave our bags, and come back later to get into our rooms. But two of our rooms were ready (we could have had all three if we didn't want to be on the same floor.), and the desk clerks were friendly and professional.The rooms themselves were large and luxurious. The bathrooms had new granite countertops; floors and tubs had obviously been recently re-tiled. Towels were large and thick. Everything was spotlessly clean, and throughout our stay, housekeeping was thorough, if a little unpredictable.It has also been noted here that the walls are paper thin. Not quite, but we could hear plumbing sounds and a neighbor with a bad cough. Construction noise from the new City Center next door was minimal. And hey, it's Vegas! Who expects peace and quiet??Two definite negatives: The daily &quot;Resort Fee&quot; is a bogus way to wring more money out of guests. We were told that it went toward bottled water and daily newspapers. Two bottles of water were present in the room when we checked in. Because we didn't drink them, we obviously were never given any more. And the newspapers are stacked by the elevator, and were gone by 9am....Negative #2: The pool CLOSES at 4PM! The pool is very nice, and I should say pools, plural. There's a large pool, a wave pool, a hot tub, and a lazy river. But it's all closed up at 4pm. No evening soaking in the hot tub. We enjoyed the pools on two afternoons, but really would have enjoyed them again in the evening. And the inner tubes for the lazy river are WAAAAY over-priced. (Shouldn't that Resort Fee cover these?)We loved the casino itself and the dealers. The buffet is spectacular, especially the Sunday Brunch. Parking is free!! And the location couldn't be better.We hadn't been to Vegas in over 10 years, and it well may be that long before we get a chance to go back, so a negative hotel experience would have really spoiled a special trip. That just didn't happen.	
Nov 10 2009 	just average but always consistent	Went here in April with a friend. (This is a late submission). I've stayed here before, and the construction was still going on, but it was expected, so again, not too much of an issue. The room was good, the value was good. What I haven't done in Vegas before was chill by the pool. ( When hubby and I go to Vegas, we're usually tied up with shopping and sightseeing) We spent our days by the pool, and our nights partying at the clubs. What a great vacation. The sun sits right in the middle of the sky and when you get too warm the lazy river cools you off just right. Let me just say the DJ and his/her mash-ups were either awesome or horrible. But the thumping of the music and crowd of people to watch... it was perfect.I didn't notice before, but there is an awfully strong floral smell emitted into the hotel that I found this time to be nauseating. In fact, my leather jacket (which stayed in my suitcase for the duration of the trip) reeked of it for weeks after.As always, the service is fine (not outstanding but not bad), the decor and cleanliness are fine. We had a poolside room which I guess if you are spending the days in your room might be an issue- the music carried up to the 27th floor and rocked our walls- but we were cool with it. (After laying by the pool all day we had to have a nap to make sure we were in shape for the night's festivities! It's a tough life!)Tip- try Jimmy Buffet's Margaritaville for an inexpensive, entertaining dinner. Or another favorite? Gonzales Y Gonzales in New York New York! That place never fails to satisfy a craving for southwestern cusine- and, you can get the mile high margaritas there too!! Another great place for dinner- The Voodoo Restaurant. Expensive and classy with awesome service and cool decor. Afterwards, head up to the VooDoo Lounge for some drinks and enjoy the view on the rooftop patio. Be advised, after 10 pm, tables are reserved for bottle service only, but with the DJ and crowd out on the patio, who wants to be sitting at a table? It's one of my favorite nightspots!The Monte Carlo isn't the Wynn, or Caesars. It's average accomodation with a great location on the strip. It's nothing extremely fancy, and is not at all a dive-joint. The pool is fantastic, the location is great, (also there's a CVS right next door and a Walgreens across the street in case you need sunblock, toiletries, etc)	
